<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900621-0082</DOCNO><DOCID>900621-0082.</DOCID><HL>   Former Officer of Unit   Of Enron Draws Term   In Prison for Scheme   ----   A Wall Street Journal News Roundup</HL><DATE>06/21/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C18</SO><CO>   ENE</CO><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><LP>   A federal judge this week sentenced the former presidentof a defunct unit of Enron Corp. to one year and one day injail for his part in an oil trading scam that cost thecompany more than $140 million.   Louis Borget pleaded guilty to charges of fraud and incometax violations stemming from accusations that he and otherofficials of the Enron Oil Corp. unit created sham trades andfalsified documents for personal financial gain. The sentencewas imposed by Judge Gerard Goettel in the federal court inWhite Plains, N.Y.</LP><TEXT>   Enron declined comment on the matter, citing pending civillitigation against Mr. Borget. Enron Oil, an internationaloil trading unit, was discontinued in 1987.   In addition to the jail sentence, Mr. Borget received fiveyears of probation and was ordered to pay $5.9 millionrestitution. He has 30 days to surrender.</TEXT></DOC>